      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A cold front forms when a dense, cold air mass advances and wedges itself beneath a warmer, less dense air mass. Because cold air is denser, it exerts greater pressure at the surface and forces the warmer air aloft, creating a steep slope known as the frontal surface. As the warm air is forced upward rapidly, it cools adiabatically, causing water vapor to condense into clouds and precipitate, which drives the sudden weather shift. The pressure drop you often feel just before the front arrives is due to the warm air aloft spreading out and lowering surface pressure, while the cold air behind the front builds up higher pressure as it settles. This dynamic interaction between the density differences and pressure gradients is what makes the transition so abrupt.",
